<div class="container">
    <h1>APIs (Application Programming Interfaces)</h1>
    <p>An <strong>API</strong> is a set of rules that allows different applications or systems to communicate with each other. APIs are essential in web communication for enabling clients to interact with servers programmatically.</p>

    <h2>Types of APIs</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>REST (Representational State Transfer):</strong> Uses HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) to access resources. Commonly returns JSON.</li>
        <li><strong>SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol):</strong> Uses XML messages and strict standards for communication.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Data Formats</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>JSON:</strong> Lightweight, easy-to-read format for data exchange.</li>
        <li><strong>XML:</strong> Verbose but highly structured, used in SOAP APIs.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example: Simple REST API Call (C# ASP.NET Core)</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Server-Side: API Controller</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
[ApiController]
[Route("api/[controller]")]
public class ProductsController : ControllerBase
{
    [HttpGet]
    public IActionResult GetProducts()
    {
        var products = _productService.GetAllProducts(); // Fetch from database
        return Ok(products); // Return JSON response
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult CreateProduct([FromBody] Product product)
    {
        _productService.AddProduct(product); // Save to database
        return CreatedAtAction(nameof(GetProducts), new { id = product.Id }, product);
    }
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Client-Side Example: Fetching Data</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Client-Side: JavaScript Fetch API</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-javascript">
fetch('https://example.com/api/products')
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(data => console.log(data))
    .catch(error => console.error('Error:', error));
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>This example demonstrates how a client can request data from a server API and receive JSON in response.</p>

